018	JOB	039	029	From thence he spieth out prey; His eyes discern it from afar.
018	JOB	039	030	His young ones suck up blood; And where the slain are, there is he.
018	JOB	040	001	Moreover Jehovah spake to Job, and said:
018	JOB	040	002	Will the censurer of the Almighty contend with him? Will the reprover of God answer?
018	JOB	040	003	Then Job answered Jehovah, and said:
018	JOB	040	004	Behold, I am vile! what can I answer thee? I will lay my hand upon my mouth.
018	JOB	040	005	Once have I spoken, but I will not speak again; Yea, twice, but I will say no more.
018	JOB	040	006	Then spake Jehovah to Job out of the whirlwind, and said:
018	JOB	040	007	Gird up now thy loins like a man! I will ask thee, and do thou instruct me!
018	JOB	040	008	Wilt thou even disannul my right? Wilt thou condemn me, that thou mayst be righteous?
018	JOB	040	009	Hast thou an arm like God's? Or canst thou thunder with thy voice like him?
018	JOB	040	010	Deck thyself with grandeur and majesty, And array thyself in splendor and glory!
018	JOB	040	011	Send forth the fury of thy wrath! Look upon every proud one, and abase him!
018	JOB	040	012	Look upon every proud one, and bring him low; Yea, tread down the wicked in their place!
018	JOB	040	013	Hide them in the dust together; Shut up their faces in darkness!
018	JOB	040	014	Then, indeed, will I give thee the praise, That thine own right hand can save thee.
018	JOB	040	015	Behold the river-horse, which I have made as well as thyself; He feedeth on grass like the ox.
018	JOB	040	016	Behold, what strength is in his loins! And what force in the muscles of his belly!
018	JOB	040	017	He bendeth his tail, like the cedar, And the sinews of his thighs are twisted together.
018	JOB	040	018	His bones are pipes of brass, And his limbs are bars of iron.
018	JOB	040	019	He is chief among the works of God; He that made him gave him his sword.
018	JOB	040	020	For the mountains supply him with food, Where all the beasts of the field play.
018	JOB	040	021	He lieth down under the lote-plants, In the covert of reeds, and in the fens.
018	JOB	040	022	The lote-plants cover him with their shadow, And the willows of the brook compass him about.
018	JOB	040	023	Lo! the stream overfloweth, but he starteth not; He is unmoved though Jordan rush forth even to his mouth.
018	JOB	040	024	Can one take him before his eyes, Or pierce his nose with hooks?
018	JOB	041	001	Canst thou draw forth the crocodile with a hook, Or press down his tongue with a cord?
018	JOB	041	002	Canst thou put a rope into his nose, Or pierce his cheek with a hook?
018	JOB	041	003	Will he make many entreaties to thee? Will he speak soft words to thee?
018	JOB	041	004	Will he make a covenant with thee? Canst thou take him for a servant for ever?
018	JOB	041	005	Canst thou play with him, as with a bird? Or canst thou bind him for thy maidens?
018	JOB	041	006	Do men in company lay snares for him? Do they divide him among the merchants?
018	JOB	041	007	Canst thou fill his skirt with barbed irons, Or his head with fish-spears?
018	JOB	041	008	Do but lay thy hand upon him, —Thou wilt no more think of battle!
018	JOB	041	009	Behold, his hope is vain! Is he not cast down at the very sight of him?
018	JOB	041	010	None is so fierce that he dare stir him up; Who then is he that can stand before me?
018	JOB	041	011	Who hath done me a favor, that I must repay him? Whatever is under the whole heaven is mine.
018	JOB	041	012	I will not be silent concerning his limbs, And his strength, and the beauty of his armor.
018	JOB	041	013	Who can uncover the surface of his garment? Who will approach his jaws?
018	JOB	041	014	Who will open the doors of his face? The rows of his teeth are terrible!
018	JOB	041	015	His glory is his strong shields, United with each other, as with a close seal.
018	JOB	041	016	They are joined one to another, So that no air can come between them.
018	JOB	041	017	They cleave fast to each other, They hold together, and cannot be separated.
018	JOB	041	018	His sneezing sendeth forth light, And his eyes are like the eyelashes of the morning.
018	JOB	041	019	Out of his mouth go flames, And sparks of fire leap forth.
018	JOB	041	020	From his nostrils issueth smoke, as from a heated pot, or caldron.
018	JOB	041	021	His breath kindleth coals, And flames issue from his mouth.
018	JOB	041	022	In his neck dwelleth strength, And terror danceth before him.
018	JOB	041	023	The flakes of his flesh cleave fast together; They are firm upon him, and cannot be moved.
018	JOB	041	024	His heart is solid like a stone; Yea, solid like the nether millstone.
018	JOB	041	025	When he riseth up, the mighty are afraid; Yea, they lose themselves for terror.
018	JOB	041	026	The sword of him that assaileth him doth not stand, The spear, the dart, nor the habergeon.
018	JOB	041	027	He regardeth iron as straw, And brass as rotten wood.
018	JOB	041	028	The arrow cannot make him flee; Sling-stones to him become stubble;
018	JOB	041	029	Clubs are accounted by him as straw; He laugheth at the shaking of the spear.
018	JOB	041	030	Under him are sharp potsherds; He spreadeth out a thrashing-sledge upon the mire.
018	JOB	041	031	He maketh the deep to boil like a caldron; He maketh the sea like a pot of ointment.
018	JOB	041	032	Behind him he leaveth a shining path; One would think the deep to be hoary.
018	JOB	041	033	Upon the earth there is not his master; He is made without fear.
018	JOB	041	034	He looketh down upon all that is high; He is king over all the sons of pride.
018	JOB	042	001	Then Job answered Jehovah, and said:
018	JOB	042	002	I know that thou canst do every thing, And that no purpose of thine can be hindered.
018	JOB	042	003	Who is he that darkeneth counsel by words without knowledge? Thus have I uttered what I understood not; Things too wonderful for me, which I knew not:
018	JOB	042	004	Hear thou, then, I beseech thee, and I will speak! I will ask thee, and do thou instruct me!
018	JOB	042	005	I have heard of thee by the hearing of the ear; But now hath mine eye seen thee.
018	JOB	042	006	Wherefore I abhor myself, And repent in dust and ashes.
018	JOB	042	007	And when Jehovah had spoken these words unto Job, he said to Eliphaz the Temanite: “My wrath is kindled against thee, and against thy two friends; for ye have not spoken concerning me that which is right, as hath my servant Job.
018	JOB	042	008	Take ye, therefore, seven bullocks and seven rams, and go to my servant Job, and offer for yourselves a burnt-offering, and my servant Job shall pray for you; for to him alone will I have regard; that I deal not with you according to your folly. For ye have not spoken concerning me that which is right, as hath my servant Job.”
018	JOB	042	009	So Eliphaz the Temanite, and Bildad the Shuhite, and Zophar the Naamathite, went and did as Jehovah commanded them; and Jehovah had regard to Job.
018	JOB	042	010	And Jehovah turned the captivity of Job, when he prayed for his friends, and Jehovah gave him twice as much as he had before.
018	JOB	042	011	Then came to him all his brethren, and all his sisters, and all his former acquaintances, and ate bread with him in his house; and condoled with him, and comforted him over all the evil which Jehovah had brought upon him; and every one gave him a piece of money [a kesita], and every one a ring of gold.
018	JOB	042	012	Thus Jehovah blessed the latter end of Job more than the beginning; for he had fourteen thousand sheep, six thousand camels, a thousand yoke of oxen, and a thousand she-asses.
018	JOB	042	013	He had also seven sons, and three daughters.
018	JOB	042	014	And he called the name of the first Jemima, of the second Kezia, and of the third Kerenhappuch.
018	JOB	042	015	And in all the land were no women found so fair as the daughters of Job; and their father gave them an inheritance among their brethren.
018	JOB	042	016	And Job lived after this a hundred and forty years, and saw his sons, and his sons' sons, even four generations.
018	JOB	042	017	Then Job died, being old and satisfied with days.
